    <stitle>FRONT NON-DRIVE STEERING AXLE: ROCKWELL - DISASSEMBLE</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec id="hl0200501">
        <title>DISASSEMBLE</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="4">
            <title>KING PINS AND STEERING KNUCKLE</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Block the rear wheels.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove wheels ends. Refer to GROUP 17 - WHEELS, RIMS AND TIRES in the CTS-5000 Master
                    Service Manual.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the brake assembly. Refer to GROUP 04 - BRAKES in the CTS-5000 Master Service
                    Manual.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the tie rod arms and the steering arms from the knuckle.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the bolts that fasten the cap to the top and the bottom of the spindle. Remove
                    the caps and the gaskets (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200508">Figure 8</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0200508" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0200508" filename="../figg02/g0200508.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 8. Cap and Gasket</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>All models covered in this service manual section use threaded draw keys.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the threaded draw keys. See the following procedure.</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Loosen the lock nut until the top of the lock nut is even with the end of the draw
                        key.
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <warning>
                            <para>Wear safe eye protection. Do not hit steel parts or tools with a steel hammer. Parts
                                or tools can break and cause serious personal injury.
                            </para>
                        </warning>
                    </specpara>
                    <specpara>
                        <caution>
                            <para>Force must be directly applied to the bottom of the nut and the end of the key. If
                                force is not directly applied, the draw key will be damaged.
                            </para>
                        </caution>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Use a brass drift and a hammer to hit the end of the nut to loosen the draw key (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0200509">Figure 9</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f0200509" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0200509" filename="../figg02/g0200509.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 9. Loosening the Draw Key</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove the nut from the draw key. Remove the draw key from the knuckle.</para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>If the bushings are not being replaced, do the following to prevent damaging the
                                bushings during king pin removal.
                            </para>
                            <seqlist>
                                <item>
                                    <para>Remove any flaring on the drift that may touch the knuckle pin.</para>
                                </item>
                                <item>
                                    <para>Wrap tape to a thickness of 1/16 inch (1.5 mm) on the end of the drift.</para>
                                </item>
                            </seqlist>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a brass drift and a hammer to remove the king pins from the knuckle (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200510">Figure 10</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0200510" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0200510" filename="../figg02/g0200510.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 10. King Pin</caption>
                </figure>
                <para>If the king pin is hard to remove, use a hydraulic king pin remover. Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s02005r_33.xml" xrefid="hl0200505">SPECIAL TOOLS</hotlnk>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <warning>
                        <para>To prevent personal injury, wear gloves when removing shims. The shims have sharp edges.
                        </para>
                    </warning>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the knuckle from the axle beam. Remove the shims, the thrust bearing and the seal
                    from between the beam and the knuckle (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200511">Figure 11</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0200511" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0200511" filename="../figg02/g0200511.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 11. Shim Removal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
